\begin_layout Standard
The massive industrialization of society over the last century has caused
 changes at a global level.
 This coupled with the influence of technology, which is developing at an
 increasing rate, has allowed the global population to rise exponentially,
 from 1.65 billion in 1900 to around 7 Billion in 2010 and is expected to
 reach 8.9 billion people by 2050 (UN WORLD POP 2300).
 At the same time as the global population has been increasing the amount
 of raw material consumed by individuals has been increasing, especially
 by in developed economies (???).
 The increase in individual demand for goods multiplied by the increase
 in global population has grown human industrial activities to the point
 where they have significantly degraded the global biosphere.
 The degradations can be evidenced in two primary ways, anthropogenic climate
 change, and ecosystem destruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
15 of the 24 key ecosystem services on which humans depend are degraded
 or are being used unsustainably (United Nations Millennium Ecosystem Assessment
, 2005 (from M swilling, UNEP) ).
 These services provide for and support basic necessities such as food productio
n and water supplies.
 The degradation of these services disproportionately affects the poor,
 and especially sub-Saharan Africa (UNMEA).
 Biodiversity, a key component of many ecosystem services, is being dramatically
 reduced by mass extinctions of species caused by the compounding effects
 of climate change and the habitat destruction caused by expanding human
 activities (thomas 2004 (lost)).
 Global ecosystem destruction is coupled with and compounded by climate
 change.
\end_layout

