\begin_layout Standard
The A1 family is defined by a a high level of globalization and homogenization
 of the global economy activity of per capita income.
 Economic growth is rapid due to the introduction of new efficient technologies.
 The increased social interactions and economic growth lead to a global
 population that peaks around mid-century.
 The A1 family is divided into 3 scenarios dependent on the spread of technologi
es used in energy generation: fossil intensive (A1FI), non-fossil energy
 sources (A1T), or a balance across all sources (A1B) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The A2 family describes a heavily regionalized and economically heterogeneous
 world.
 The decreased global interaction and cooperation leads to economic and
 fertility patterns not rapidly converging between regions.
 This fragmentation leads to slow economic and technological growth as well
 as a continuously increasing population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The B1 storyline describes a similarly globalized world as the A1 world
 but with drastic change in economic emphasis toward service and information
 sectors with corresponding decreases in material intensity, as well the
 large scale introduction clean and efficiency increasing technologies.
 Form these focuses emarge global solutions to economic, social and ecological
 sustainability, in terms of both inter- and intra-generational equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The B2 storyline envisages a regionalized world much like A2 but with local
 policy makers emphasizing sustainable solutions to socio-economic and ecologica
l problems.
 The result is slower, though continuously, increasing population and less
 economic growth and rapid technological development than in the A1 and
 B1 story lines.
 While there are many efforts towards environmental protection they lack
 the global coordination of A2 and are bound by local regions.
\end_layout

